        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94cbf036e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>3:1.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Jurisdiction of Panel generally</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The powers of the Panel are defined by the statute creating it, <cite.query
                            w-src-number="0304913949" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ"
                            w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546"
                            ID="I0c377bf0680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407</cite.query>.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I021735b0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>] The powers
                        set forth in the statute can also be thought of as the limits of the Panel&apos;s jurisdiction,
                        since the Panel has no other authority for taking any action in a case.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The statute authorizes the Panel to order transfer of pending actions to any district for
                        pretrial proceedings and to remand part or all of those actions to the district court in which
                        they were initially filed.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I02175cc0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">2</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        does not have the power to enter any other orders in the actions.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel does not take any action of a substantive or procedural nature <?pagebreak label="20"?> other than
                        transfer or remand cases.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>These matters are left to the discretion of either the transferor court as to matters
                        arising prior to transfer or after remand or the transferee court as to matters arising in the
                        litigation following transfer by the Panel but before remand.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I0217f901680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        cannot expand its jurisdiction by entering transfer or remand orders conditioned on the
                        performance of matters not properly within its limited jurisdiction.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I02182012680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">4</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The function of the Panel is essentially managerial, not adjudicative.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Although the Panel receives motions, hears arguments, considers briefs, and issues
                        decisions, it does not really adjudicate the rights of litigants.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel recognizes that there is no “right” to transfer under the
                        statute,[<footnote.reference refid="I021a9112680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">5</footnote.reference>]
                        and that a party does not assert or waive transfer “rights.”[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I021ab820680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">6</footnote.reference>] Similarly,
                        the Panel can act <ital>sua sponte</ital> in its transfer decisions and can order transfer if
                        all parties oppose it.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I021ba280680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">7</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel was also given by Congress the task of assigning the judges to the special
                        federal court created under the Regional Rail Reorganization Act of 1973.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I021c17b1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">8</footnote.reference>] This duty
                        is discussed in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:17"
                                                    w-pub-number="185218" ID="I021c8ce0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">§
                            3:17</cite.query>.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In 1988 the Panel was given the responsibility to consider multicircuit appeals from
                        orders of administrative agencies and boards.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>This authority is discussed in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA"
                                                                         w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:18"
                                                                         w-pub-number="185218"
                                                                         ID="I021cdb00680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">§
                            3:18</cite.query>.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel has adopted the term “centralization” to describe its action where transfer is
                        ordered.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>This term is both clear and more precise than referring to transfer in that where the
                        Panel does decide to transfer cases to a single district all cases are centralized in a single
                        district, but not all are transferred—the cases that where already pending in that district
                        before the transferee judge are not transferred but simply remain there.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>If there are cases in the transferee district that are not already before the transferee
                        court, they are really just reassigned rather than transferred to a different district.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Centralization is a broader term that encompasses the Panel&apos;s action for any of these
                        cases. <?pagebreak label="21"?>[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I021cdb01680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">9</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
